Ask HN: Investigating EM Noise
text:
For the past few months I've been having absolutely horrible wi-fi issues. I've been trying to get to the root of the problem for some time now and I'm at the point where I'm grasping at straws. Essentially, I've been experiencing really terrible, yet inconsistent, packet loss on the order of 10-25%. It's a daily problem, but I've made little headway on solving it because I can't seem to correlate anything I do with the issue.

Here's an overview of what's happening and what's been investigated: - First of all, I haven't always had this issue. I've been in this house for 2 years now, and didn't have any problems until earlier this year. - I first started seeing problems with Zoom. Specifically my outgoing packets. If I look at the Zoom statistics, I'll receive 1080p video at 30fps but my outgoing video will be 180p and under 10fps typically. I'll often see 30%+ packet loss on the outgoing requests. - It's slowly gotten worse as general web browsing hangs a lot. By which I mean, it'll regularly but randomly take a second or so for a website to resolve (and I'm talking big highly available services). - I got to the point where I thought this was related to my ISP. They've sent multiple techs out. They've replaced the modem, the splitters on the cable, etc. Interestingly they noticed that there were maintenance issues with our local box, but even after those were addressed the problems have persisted. So it looks like the connection to the ISP is fine (I'm not seeing any codeword errors on my modem which I once did). - Following all of that, my ISP ended up sending a specialist because apparently there's a lot of noise at my house. I live in a town house. The neighbours to my left and right have both changed in the past few months. Seeing as how my network topology has not changed in well over a year, and I didn't have this issue to begin with, that leads me to believe they might be the issue? - It's really affecting my Macs more than anything. If I do a packet loss test, they'll have rolling spikes of up to 200-400ms, where a baseline would be more like 40ms. Interestingly, my gaming laptop will see 60ms flat while the Macs will be spiking. - My girlfriend has been having problems with her Bluetooth mouse. Full battery, but the mouse will skip, miss clicks, etc. - Seems to happen at all hours. Especially a problem during the day, but it happens at night too.

With all that in mind, what should I be doing next? The ISP has found a lot of noise in my immediate vicinity, how might I find the root of the issue? I'm not sure what tools I'd need to investigate that myself. It's driving me insane (I have to spend a lot of time on Zoom these days, and it's affecting my work).

Show HN: Bell inequality violation with entangled photons - Nobel Prize 2022
text:
This year Nobel Prize in Physics was awarded to Alain Aspect, John F. Clauser, and Anton Zeilinger - for "experiments with entangled photons, establishing the violation of Bell inequalities, and pioneering quantum information science".

If you want to simulate the Bell inequality violation in your browser, you can do so in the Virtual Lab by Quantum Flytrap. We use the Clauser-Horne-Shimony-Holt.

There are quite a few other examples of quantum information experimental setups related to the winners. For example, a GHZ (Greenberger-Horne-Zeilinger) source, which creates quantum states with intrinsic three-photon entanglement.

For a more detailed description, see Section 5. Example Experiments in our open-access publication on the lab: https://doi.org/10.1117/1.OE.61.8.081808

Show HN: Tour of CLIPS
text:
Learn how to write Rules Engines with CLIPS in your browser! I found the Tour of Go super useful when learning Go, so I went for something similar for evangelizing the awesomeness of CLIPS.

A few things I'm proud of with this project:

- No front-end frameworks - Compiled WASM binary; your code isn't sent to a back-end server - Code editor/syntax highlighter written from scratch (that I'm sure you'll find bugs in ;))

This is my first attempt at this, and I'd like to expand on it in the future. Let me know what you think!

About CLIPS: CLIPS is a programming language useful for building Rules Engines and Expert Systems. It's written in C, so it's pretty darned easy to put data in/get data out from other languages written in C. It was started in the mid-80s at NASA, and it was released to the public in the mid-90s. It's still in active development by the original developer.

title: Ask HN: Privacy Friendly Local Grammar Checker?
text:
Hello all,

I went online today to look for a grammar checker to help me proofread my articles and stories. I kept finding notes in the privacy policies, or discussions online (eg, "Is Grammarly a Keylogger?" https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=30470457), that made me pause before sigining up for anything.

Can anybody recommend a grammar checker that doesn't send your content to a server?

Ask HN: HP Dev One, any buyers remorse?
text:
I'm switching companies, and will be assigned a beefy Windows 10 laptop. WSL2 has been a good developer experience, so I'm not disappointed about going non-Mac.

That said I need a new personal machine, and while I have a few MacBook Pros, I'm disappointed with their lack of expandability (RAM), and more so that they won't take the latest macOS versions (without workarounds that have caveats). Was not a problem until I found apps I use won't upgrade because the OS won't upgrade.

The HP Dev One may not be the best in class option for a laptop that ships with Linux, but for the price it checks most of my boxes. Upgradable, works with multiple distros (Pop OS is nice enough), reasonable cost.

I have seen comments about the screen resolution. But not knowing too much about the panel options today, don't know if that would be a problem for me. My comparison would be a 2015 MacBook Pro Retina, the last 15" or less laptop I worked on.

I mostly work in a terminal, Vim: SQL, Python, Go. Desktop environment is for a browser, email, chat UI, and little else.

Anyone with this specific laptop wish they did not buy it, and if so, why?

Ask HN: How does a Mac determine your location during set-up?
text: A friend just brought me a Macbook Air (2019) to Greece where I am currently located. The computer came from another European country and was reset to factory settings before the trip. When I started the setup, Greece was pre-selected on the country/region picker before even connecting the computer to a network. How is this possible?
